      "patchset_number": 10,
      "line": 155,
      "message": "Regarding vFirewall, the actor code does this:\n\n  cq.getGenericVnfByModelInvariantId(target-resource-id)\n\nSo the target resource ID just has to match one of the model invariants within the CQ response.  Whether or not it's a valid resource ID doesn't really matter, as long as the CQ response class can find it.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2020-09-01 16:31:25.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "780a12a1_bef73064",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "aa545810_087a3656",
      "file_path": "controlloop/common/controller-usecases/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/apps/controller/usecases/step/GuardStep2.java",
      "patchset_number": 10,
      "line": 155,
      "message": "Those directories are exactly what I'm looking at which is why I think the vFirewall is specified incorrectly - but there is no custom query information in those directories. The vFirewall should be a vnf-id, not a modelInvariantId (that's for vDNS). It has to be able to dynamically find the correct vnf/vserver/model information based on what the policy designer specified. Every use case passes data differently.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 57,
        "name": "Pamela Dragosh",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "pd1248@att.com",
        "username": "pdragosh"
      },
      "updated": "2020-09-01 18:04:27.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "17d91205_af167e6e",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "f9b40ee4_1a18d985",
      "file_path": "controlloop/common/controller-usecases/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/apps/controller/usecases/step/GuardStep2.java",
      "patchset_number": 10,
      "line": 155,
      "message": "I can't answer that.  All I can say is that vFirewall uses the VNF, but it FINDS the VNF whose model invariant ID matches  the target-resource-id.  That is unchanged from prior releases (i.e., Casablanca and Dublin both worked the same way).",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2020-09-01 19:13:24.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "aa545810_087a3656",
      "unresolved": true
    },
